This is a textbook example of a clean, modern, production-ready email service in .NET.

In enterprise applications, Microsoft explicitly recommends against using the built-in System.Net.Mail.SmtpClient (which is now considered legacy). Instead, you are correctly using MailKit and MimeKit, which are the industry gold standards for secure email transmission in C#.

Here is a senior-level breakdown of exactly how this code works, divided into three main architectural steps.

Step 1: Configuration & The Constructor
Before the service can send an email, it needs to know your SMTP server details (like SendGrid, AWS SES, or Gmail).

C#
private readonly EmailSettings _emailSettings;

public EmailService(IConfiguration configuration)
{
    _emailSettings = configuration
        .GetSection("EmailSettings")
        .Get<EmailSettings>()!;
}
IConfiguration configuration: The .NET Dependency Injection engine hands this class a map of your appsettings.json file.

The Binding Matrix: Instead of reading string values one by one (which is prone to typos), you use the Options Pattern. The code goes to the "EmailSettings" block in your JSON file and automatically maps those values into a strongly-typed C# class called EmailSettings.

The ! Operator: The exclamation mark at the end is the "null-forgiving operator". It tells the C# compiler: "I promise this configuration section exists in the JSON file and will not be null, so don't throw a warning."

Step 2: Constructing the Payload (MimeKit)
When you call SendAsync, the first half of the method is dedicated to building the actual email package in memory.

C#
var email = new MimeMessage();
email.From.Add(MailboxAddress.Parse(_emailSettings.From));
email.To.Add(MailboxAddress.Parse(to));
email.Subject = subject;

email.Body = new TextPart("html") { Text = body };
MimeMessage: This is the standard internet format for email.

MailboxAddress.Parse(): This safely converts a plain string like "support@bank.com" into a structured email address object that mail servers understand.

new TextPart("html"): This is a critical security and formatting detail. By explicitly specifying "html", you are telling the recipient's email client (like Outlook or Gmail) to render HTML tags (like <b> or <a>) instead of just displaying raw code to the user.

Step 3: The SMTP Delivery Pipeline (MailKit)
The second half of the method is the actual network execution. It opens a socket to the internet, delivers the payload, and closes the door.

C#
using var smtp = new SmtpClient();

await smtp.ConnectAsync(_emailSettings.Host, _emailSettings.Port, SecureSocketOptions.StartTls);
await smtp.AuthenticateAsync(_emailSettings.Username, _emailSettings.Password);
await smtp.SendAsync(email);
await smtp.DisconnectAsync(true);
using var smtp: As we discussed in your previous memory management lessons, the using keyword guarantees that the network port is instantly closed and disposed of the millisecond this method finishes, preventing server memory leaks.

ConnectAsync with StartTls: This is vital for a financial application. StartTls tells the mail server: "We might be connecting on an insecure port initially, but we demand you instantly upgrade this connection to TLS encryption before we send any passwords."

AuthenticateAsync: You log in to your mail provider.

SendAsync: The payload is fired over the network.

DisconnectAsync(true): The true parameter tells the server to send a polite "QUIT" command to the SMTP server, closing the handshake cleanly rather than just dropping the connection.

Architectural Summary
Because this class implements the IEmailService interface, your Controllers or other Services (like the CustomerService when a user registers) can easily inject IEmailService and call SendAsync without ever needing to know what MailKit is, or whether the email is going through AWS, Google, or Mailgun!